# Ansible Controller Setup Notes

This file is a quick reference for preparing an Ansible control node and building the first static inventory.

## 1. Install Ansible

On RHEL or CentOS style systems:

```bash
yum install epel-release
yum install ansible -y
```

Or with `dnf`:

```bash
dnf install ansible -y
```

## 2. Install Git

```bash
yum install git -y
```

## 3. Prepare Hostname Resolution

Update `/etc/hosts` if your lab or environment depends on static hostname mappings.

## 4. Create The `ansible` User On The Control Node

```bash
useradd ansible
passwd ansible
```

## 5. Validate Local Connectivity

Before setting up all remote nodes, test that the Ansible user can run a basic module against localhost.

```bash
ansible localhost -m ping -k
```

Expected behavior is a successful ping response after entering the SSH password.

## 6. Create The `ansible` User On Managed Nodes

```bash
useradd ansible
passwd ansible
```

Create the same automation user on each managed host when you are using a shared lab account model.

## 7. Build A Basic Inventory

Edit the default inventory file:

```bash
nano /etc/ansible/hosts
```

Example entries:

```ini
localhost
node1.mslab.net
node2.mslab.net
```

## 8. Grant Sudo Access

Allow the `ansible` user to escalate privileges without being prompted every time.

```bash
visudo
```

Example rule:

```text
ansible ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL
```

## 9. Configure SSH Key-Based Access

Switch to the automation user and create an SSH key pair:

```bash
su - ansible
ssh-keygen
```

Copy the public key to each managed host:

```bash
ssh-copy-id node2.mslab.net
ssh-copy-id node1.mslab.net
ssh-copy-id localhost
```

Verify access:

```bash
ssh node2.mslab.net
ssh node1.mslab.net
```

## 10. Review Configuration Sources

List available Ansible configuration settings:

```bash
ansible-config list
```

Inventory location can come from:

- the default path: `/etc/ansible/hosts`
- the CLI with `ansible -i <filename>`
- an `ansible.cfg` file

## 11. Inventory Examples

```ini
[webservers]
httpd1.example.com
httpd2.example.com

[labservers]
lab[01:99]
```

## Notes

- This is a lab-oriented setup reference, not a hardened production build guide.
- In shared environments, review SSH, sudo, and inventory standards before applying these steps unchanged.
